<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Hey, I think that we should all stop flaming and calling names. of course, I'm a wiz, so I do like a good flame. I just think that hey, we take out all of the name calling, and look at the debate, one thing strikes me as the most common sensical view on this issue:<P>Mages are broken in the high-end game? I cannot speak from experience, but I have seen enough (and consistent) complaints from high level mage players to think it's a pretty valid gripe. My brother plays a level 57 Wizard on Vazaelle, and he is the most intelligent fellow I know personally, and he feels the same way. Again, I cannot speak from experience, but I would like to think that I speak from the perspective of an intelligent, level-headed adult who isn't afraid to look at all the information available and seek out truths in the postings of someone he is debating with as well as fallacies.<P>So: Yes. I am very inclined to believe that, at the high-end, mages need work.<P>My point..and honestly, the point I think should be taken fairly seriously by our mage friends, is as I stated earlier: Two wrongs do not make a right.<P>Mages should be tweaked. Made better in the areas where they are sorely lacking. I think that's not a terribly unreasonable thing to say.<P>But they are not meant to be the best DD dealers in the game. DD is not their primary focus. Pets are. Elemental summoning and control. It can be argued that this obviously would mean elemental dd as well, but I think it is fairly obvious that the Wizard was created to have THAT as his/her purview.<P>If magicians have an inferior pet at high level (in relation to Necromancers and Beastlords), then perhaps that needs to be addressed. Their pets or pet buffs. Something to do with their pets. Poo poo the direct damage, maybe that should be increased a miniscule amount (I am NOT taking a stance on that one) but crits...no. Give the Wizards something, please. Crits, for example, did not in any way overpower my little 37th level Wizard, but they did make me feel special, and happier with the class.<P>My little putzly mage is up to level 12 now, and I can tell you that, in the LOW end game, at least, my limited experience points to the fact that Mages -rock- hard over wizards. I'm having a lot of fun with my mage.<P>But I am still a Wiz at heart, and I honestly don't want to turn into a mage with ports instead of pets. Classes are meant to be different. Each have strengths and weaknesses, and that is cool. Hell, my poor little wiz would be mincemeat if forced into melee against anything. My level 12 MAGE was in oasis yesterday and got a Spec trained on him. A spec! My pet (earth) jumped in, and kept it busy while I stepped back, MEMMED gate), stood up and kicked it off, escaping with my life.<P>If that would have been my Wizard at level 12? CR time. Been there plenty of times.<P>That is the (supposed) strength of the Magician class. Their pet. Forget what anyone at the big V says, mages are not the same with or without their pet. The pet is part of what they do, and yes...they should be able to do it well.<P>I hear the Mage epic is harder than hell. perhaps that should be addressed. More pet focus items, and reducing or removing the xp penalty for pet kills. Whatever the case, there are a LOT of things which could be done to make the Magician class more viable at the high end game, in xp grind groups, etc, that could be done without bending another class (Wizards) over and giving them the ol' prison welcome treatment.<P>Pets. Pets. Pets. Pets.<P>Mage.<P>Pet. Pet. Pet. Pet.<P>Istark Kirtan<BR>37th Level Wizard<BR>Morell-Thule<P>--------------------<P>"Tell them....I said something."<P>--Last words of Pancho Villa
</FONT>
